    <section id="types">
      <h2>1. Types of Part-Time Jobs for Beginners</h2>
      <p>Part-time jobs that require no experience fall into a few well-defined categories. Each has different demands, pay structures, and working environments. Understanding the landscape helps you target the ones that fit your schedule, personality, and income needs.</p>

      <h3>Retail</h3>
      <p>Retail positions — sales associate, cashier, stock clerk — are among the most common entry-level part-time jobs. Major chains (Target, Walmart, CVS, Walgreens, Home Depot, grocery chains) hire year-round for part-time roles. The work involves customer interaction, operating a register, restocking shelves, and keeping the store organised.</p>
      <p>Retail is a strong option if you are comfortable with standing for long periods and dealing with the public. Most retailers provide on-the-job training, and many offer a clear path from part-time to full-time and even management.</p>

      <h3>Food Service &amp; Hospitality</h3>
      <p>Restaurants, cafes, fast-food chains, and hotels regularly hire beginners. Common roles include:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Server / waiter:</strong> taking orders, serving food, handling payments. Requires good memory and people skills. Tips often double the base hourly wage.</li>
        <li><strong>Host / hostess:</strong> greeting customers, managing waitlists, answering phones. One of the easiest roles to start in.</li>
        <li><strong>Barista:</strong> making coffee drinks, handling a register, keeping the work area clean. Starbucks and local cafes hire beginners regularly.</li>
        <li><strong>Busser / dishwasher:</strong> clearing tables, washing dishes, basic kitchen support. No customer interaction required.</li>
        <li><strong>Hotel front desk / housekeeping:</strong> checking guests in and out, cleaning rooms. Hotels often hire for weekend and evening shifts.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Food service is one of the most forgiving industries for beginners because turnover is high and training cycles are short. Many roles pay most of their real value in tips.</p>

      <h3>Warehouse &amp; Delivery</h3>
      <p>Warehouse and delivery roles have grown significantly with the expansion of e-commerce. These are physically demanding but pay above minimum wage in most markets.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Warehouse associate / packer:</strong> picking, packing, and shipping orders. Amazon, UPS, FedEx, and regional fulfilment centres hire constantly.</li>
        <li><strong>Delivery driver (company-owned):</strong> driving a company vehicle to deliver packages. UPS, FedEx, Amazon DSPs, and local couriers.</li>
        <li><strong>Gig delivery:</strong> using your own vehicle to deliver food or groceries. DoorDash, Uber Eats, Instacart — you set your own hours and start within days of approval.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Gig Economy &amp; App-Based Work</h3>
      <p>App-based platforms let you start earning with no interview and no fixed schedule. These are the fastest option for immediate income but lack the stability of an employer-based role.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Rideshare driving:</strong> Uber, Lyft — pick up passengers in your car. Best in dense urban areas.</li>
        <li><strong>Food delivery:</strong> DoorDash, Uber Eats, Grubhub — deliver restaurant meals. Active in most U.S. cities.</li>
        <li><strong>Grocery delivery / shopping:</strong> Instacart, Shipt — shop and deliver groceries.</li>
        <li><strong>Pet sitting / dog walking:</strong> Rover, Wag — set your own rates and schedule.</li>
        <li><strong>Task-based:</strong> TaskRabbit — assemble furniture, clean, move boxes, etc.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Gig work is ideal for flexible schedules but comes with vehicle costs, self-employment tax, and no benefits. Treat it as a near-term income option while you pursue more stable work.</p>

      <h3>Customer Service (Call Centres &amp; Remote)</h3>
      <p>Many companies outsource entry-level customer service to call centres or remote teams. These roles involve answering phone calls, emails, or live chats from customers. Most provide paid training and require no prior experience — just a reliable internet connection if remote and a professional phone manner.</p>
      <p>Large employers include Concentrix, Teleperformance, TTEC, Alorica, and Sitel. Remote customer service is one of the best options for people who cannot commute or prefer to work from home.</p>

      <h3>Tutoring &amp; Childcare</h3>
      <p>If you are strong in a particular subject (math, English, science) or patient with children, tutoring and babysitting are accessible part-time options.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Tutor:</strong> work through agencies or platforms like Tutor.com, Wyzant, or Varsity Tutors. In-person tutoring at local learning centres also hires beginners.</li>
        <li><strong>Babysitter / nanny:</strong> care.com, Sittercity, or local referrals. No experience needed if you have references from family or neighbours.</li>
        <li><strong>After-school program assistant:</strong> YMCA, Boys &amp; Girls Clubs, local recreation centres — supervise children in structured activities.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

