    <section id="where">
      <h2>3. Where to Find Part-Time Jobs Near You</h2>
      <p>Knowing where to look is half the battle. Here are the most effective channels for finding entry-level part-time jobs in your area.</p>

      <h3>General Job Boards (Best for Variety)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Indeed:</strong> The largest job board by volume. Filter by "part-time" and "entry level." Many retail and warehouse applications go through Indeed directly.</li>
        <li><strong>Snagajob:</strong> Purpose-built for hourly and part-time work. Strong for retail, food service, and warehouse roles.</li>
        <li><strong>Glassdoor:</strong> Good for seeing salary ranges and company reviews alongside listings.</li>
        <li><strong>LinkedIn:</strong> Increasingly strong for part-time remote customer service and administrative roles. Enable the "part-time" filter in your job search.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Gig &amp; App-Based Platforms (Best for Immediate Start)</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>DoorDash / Uber Eats / Grubhub:</strong> Sign up, pass a background check (usually 2–5 days), and start delivering.</li>
        <li><strong>Uber / Lyft:</strong> Requires a newer car (typically 15–21 years old depending on city), driver's license, and insurance.</li>
        <li><strong>Instacart / Shipt:</strong> Shop and deliver groceries. Approval is usually within a week.</li>
        <li><strong>Rover / Wag:</strong> Create a profile with your rates and availability. Pet owners book you directly.</li>
        <li><strong>TaskRabbit:</strong> List the tasks you are willing to do (cleaning, moving, assembly). Clients hire you by the hour.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Direct Company Career Pages (Best for Stability)</h3>
      <p>Large employers with high turnover post part-time roles on their own career pages before they appear on job boards. Check these directly:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Retail:</strong> Target, Walmart, Costco, CVS, Walgreens, Home Depot, Lowe's, Kroger, Trader Joe's</li>
        <li><strong>Warehouse:</strong> Amazon (hiring.force.com), UPS (upsjobs.com), FedEx (careers.fedex.com)</li>
        <li><strong>Food service:</strong> Starbucks, Chick-fil-A, McDonald's, Panera, Chipotle — each has a career site</li>
        <li><strong>Remote customer service:</strong> Concentrix, Teleperformance, TTEC — check their careers pages directly</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Temp Agencies (Best if You Are Unsure)</h3>
      <p>Temporary staffing agencies place workers in short-term part-time roles with no experience required. They are an excellent entry point if you are unsure what type of work suits you. Local agencies and national chains like Robert Half, Kelly Services, Manpower, and Express Employment Professionals all place entry-level candidates.</p>
      <p>There is no cost to you — the employer pays the agency. You can try different types of work without committing. Many temp-to-hire placements convert to permanent roles after 90 days.</p>

      <h3>Local Networking (The Underrated Channel)</h3>
      <p>Small businesses — local restaurants, independent retailers, daycare centres, cleaning services — often hire through word-of-mouth or a sign in the window rather than posting online. Walk in during a quiet time (mid-morning on a weekday), ask to speak to a manager, and express interest in any part-time opening.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="online">
      <h2>4. Online &amp; Remote Part-Time Jobs (No Experience)</h2>
      <p>If you cannot commute or prefer to work from home, several categories of remote part-time work do not require experience. These are growing fast — the remote part-time job market has expanded roughly 15% year-over-year through 2025–2026.</p>

      <h3>Remote Customer Service Representative</h3>
      <p>As noted above, call centre and chat support roles are the most common remote entry-level jobs. Most provide 2–4 weeks of paid training. You need a quiet space, a reliable internet connection, and a professional demeanour on the phone.</p>
      <p>Where to find them: Indeed, FlexJobs (paid membership but high-quality listings), Rat Race Rebellion (curated remote jobs list), and the career pages of Concentrix, Teleperformance, TTEC, Alorica, and LiveOps.</p>

      <h3>Data Entry</h3>
      <p>Data entry involves entering information into spreadsheets, databases, or systems. No experience is required for most roles — just typing accuracy and attention to detail. Pay typically ranges from $14–$20 per hour for part-time positions.</p>
      <p>Caution: data entry is one of the most common categories for job scams. Never pay for a data entry job or provide bank details before being hired. Legitimate companies do not charge you to work.</p>

      <h3>Online Tutoring</h3>
      <p>Platforms like Tutor.com, Wyzant, Varsity Tutors, and Chegg Tutors hire subject-matter experts. You do not need a teaching degree or prior paid teaching experience — you need to pass a subject exam and demonstrate you can explain concepts clearly.</p>
      <p>Pay: $12–$25/hour on platforms; $25–$50+ if you build your own client base. Peak demand is after school hours and on weekends, which makes this a natural part-time fit.</p>

      <h3>Transcription</h3>
      <p>Transcription involves converting audio recordings into text. Entry-level transcriptionists work through platforms like Rev, TranscribeMe, and GoTranscript. Pay averages $12–$20 per audio hour for beginners (roughly 4 hours of work per audio hour at first, improving with practice).</p>
      <p>Transcription is solitary, detail-oriented work. Good hearing, fast typing, and familiarity with grammar conventions matter more than experience.</p>

      <h3>Website &amp; App Testing</h3>
      <p>Platforms like UserTesting, Userlytics, and TryMyUI pay users $10–$60 per 15–30 minute session to test websites and apps while speaking their thoughts aloud. No technical skills needed. Sessions are irregular but add up to $30–$300/month for active testers.</p>

      <h3>Freelance Writing (Entry Level)</h3>
      <p>If you can write clear, readable prose, entry-level freelance writing is accessible. Content mills and agencies pay $0.03–$0.08 per word for beginner writers — roughly $30–$80 per 1,000-word article. Platforms like Upwork, Fiverr, and ProBlogger list entry-level writing gigs.</p>
      <p>The key to getting started: write 3–5 unpaid sample articles on topics you know, use them as your portfolio, and pitch businesses or blogs directly.</p>
    </section>

